Noah Miller GitHub Python Project 4: Intro to Deep Neural Networks using GPU¶

In this notebook, I will be using Tensorflow, Keras, and my RTX 2060 Super to build a couple of deep neural networks to classify images. The model I will build will be to classify how many fingers a picture of a hand is holding up. This moodel will be trained on a Graphics Processing Unit (GPU) which, due to its thousands of CUDA cores, make it excellent for parallel operations. These cores make GPUs excellent for training neural networks.

The data source for the fingers data set comes from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/koryakinp/fingers.

Part 1: Importing Packages and Data¶

First, let's import the necessary packahes and data we will be using. First, I will be surpressing warnings just for the sake of keeping this notebook clean. From there I am also importing Tensorflow and Keras, which will be the library on top of which we build our deep neural networks. We will use NumPy for transforming images into arrays and OS and Glob to tell Python where to search for these images. PIL enables us to read in images and apply some necessary transformations. RE is used for string manipulations. We are importing the shuffle method from random so that our list of images is read in a random order. This prevents us from needing to randomly shuffle after the data has been read in; the shuffling happens before. Finally, I'm using backend from Keras to help free GPU memory.

Now, let's import our data. Although the data comes from the source split into testing and training folders, I want to mix these up to ensure there exists no bias between the two. All of the pictures will be read in at once, but the order in which they are read is randomly shuffled.

In [4]:
def images_import(parent_folder):
    x_data = []  # This is where the numpy arrays will be stored
    y_data = []  # This is where the labels will be stored
    image_files = glob.glob(parent_folder + "/**/*.png", recursive = True)  # Opens all sub-files (train and test folders)
    shuffle(image_files)  # For testing, we can randomly shuffle not and split later
    for imag in image_files:  # imag represents the file name
        img = Image.open(imag).convert('L').resize((128, 128), Image.ANTIALIAS)
        # convert('L') means to apply grayscale, resize(128,128) means to make the image 128 by 128 pixels
        img = np.array(img)  # Converts the image into a NumPy array
        x_data.append(img)  # Appends this new array into our list of observations
        # Now I'm identifying labels according to the file name. This involves parsing some strings
        label = int(re.findall(r'\d+',imag[-7:])[0])  # Explanation below
        # These files are labelled according to which hand (left or right) and how many fingers are held up.
        # I am only interested in the number, so the label pulls from the file name according to the number of fingers
        # These numbers are found in the last 7 characters of the file name's string
        y_data.append(label)  # Appends label (number of fingers) to target list
    
    return np.array(x_data), np.array(y_data)  # These must be returned as NumPy arrays
        
        
x_data, y_data = images_import('/home/noah/Downloads/fingers')  # This is the directory which contrains our images
x_data = x_data/255  # Normalizes pizels according to shading

Part 2: Preparing Data for Model¶

Now let's see the size of our data before a testing and training split.

In [6]:
x_data.shape[0]  # Returns number of images in x_data
Out[6]:
21600

Our data consists of 21,600 samples. This makes sense since it is the sum of the number of samples in the original source's training set (18,000) and the number of samples in the testing set (3,600).

For training and testing, I prefer to split my data roughly according to a 75/25 split. This would mean that 16,200 samples would exist in our training set and 5,400 samples would exist in our testing set, which is a significant split from the original dataset's split. The code below will automatically split according to our desired ratio.

In [7]:
x_train = x_data[0:int(x_data.shape[0]*.75)]
y_train = y_data[0:int(y_data.shape[0]*.75)]
x_test = x_data[int(x_data.shape[0]*.75): int(x_data.shape[0])]
y_test = y_data[int(x_data.shape[0]*.75):int(x_data.shape[0])]

Next, we need to let Keras know these are categorical variables since we're essentially classifying the hands into different groups depending on how many fingers are held up. There are six categories since this includes any amount of fingers being held up from 1 to 5 as well as cases in which no fingers are held up.

In [8]:
y_train_keras = keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train, num_classes = 6)
y_test_keras = keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test, num_classes = 6)

Part 3: Defining the Model¶

Finally, before we can train the model, we need to define the model. This model is extremely simple; it contains only an input later with a shape of 128 by 128 (matching the dimensions of our images) and an output later with 6 neurons, matching the number of classes for which we want to predict. We are using stochastic gradient descent for our optimizer, a powerful tool which works to minimize errors while training by randomly iterating through parameters which minimize our loss function.

In [9]:
def get_model():
    model = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(128,128,1)),  # Input layer
    keras.layers.Dense(6, activation='sigmoid')  # Output layer
    ])

    model.compile(optimizer='SGD',
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

Part 4: Training Model¶

Finally, we may begin to train our model. Using the context manager, we can specify which device we want to train our model on. Here, I'm essentially choosing the first GPU available. This can be changed to "with tf.device('/CPU:0'):" for those who with to run on CPUs instead. In the future, I would like to see what it is like to train on multiple GPUs at once as well.

In [10]:
with tf.device('/GPU:0'):  # Telling tensorflow which device (GPU vs CPU) to use
    model_gpu = get_model()  # Defining the model to use
    model_gpu.fit(x_train, y_train_keras, epochs = 5)  # Training model for 10 epochs
    score, accuracy = model_gpu.evaluate(x_test, y_test_keras)  # Seeing how we performed; mostly using accuracy
    K.clear_session()
    print(f"Model accuracy on testing data: {accuracy}")  # Prints accuracy
    predictions = model_gpu.predict(x_test)

I chose to train this model on 5 epochs in order to not overfit. Likewise, this data is relatively simple as far as images are concerned, so training should not take too long anyway. We can see this model converged extremely fast and its accuracy score was nearly perfect on data it had not seen before!

y_test_incorrect = []
class_predictions_incorrect = []
for imag in range(len(y_test)):
    if y_test[imag] != classes[imag]:
        x_test_incorrect.append(x_test[imag])
        y_test_incorrect.append(y_test[imag])
        class_predictions_incorrect.append(classes[imag])
